Good catch. Two possibilities here:

### A) It’s just a VS Code lint warning (most likely)
Your editor is flagging an unknown **at‑rule**. Tailwind uses special at‑rules (like `@tailwind`, `@layer`). Some linters also misread “**@theme**” even if it isn’t actually in use.

- Quick fix in VS Code: create (or edit) `.vscode/settings.json`:
```json
{
  "css.lint.unknownAtRules": "ignore",
  "scss.lint.unknownAtRules": "ignore",
  "less.lint.unknownAtRules": "ignore"
}
```
This silences the bogus warning. If the site compiles and runs, you’re fine.

### B) There’s an actual `@theme` line in `globals.css`
Tailwind v3 (what you have by default) doesn’t use `@theme`. Remove it.

Open `src/app/globals.css` and make sure the **top** looks exactly like this (and nothing with `@theme` in the file):
```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

/* your custom styles below */
```

Then keep our chaotic background we added **appended at the bottom**.

---

