@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

So you’d just replace:  
```css
@theme
```
with one of the above that fits where it’s sitting.  

If `@theme` was right at the top before anything else, then it’s almost certainly meant to be `@tailwind base;` followed by `@tailwind components;` and `@tailwind utilities;`.  

Do you want me to rewrite the exact top of your `globals.css` for how it *should* look before we add your chaotic background?

Ah, gotcha — so it’s actually `@theme inline` (or `@themesInline` depending on the syntax your file has) sitting in there, and your CSS language server doesn’t recognize it.  

That’s **not** a standard Tailwind or Next.js directive — it’s probably from a theme or template you copied that used a CSS preprocessor feature. In plain Tailwind, you don’t need it at all.  

So your safest move: **delete that whole `@themesInline` line**.  

Your `globals.css` should just go:  
```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

:root {
  /* your variables here */
}
```

…and then after all your other styles, append the chaotic background code I gave you.  

