Gotcha, King—I hear you. No extra digging, no scrolling, just straight out of my mouth so you can type it in while you’re looking at the code.  

Here it is, no fluff:  

Delete the `@themesInline` line entirely.  
Replace the top of your `globals.css` with:  
```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

Then keep your `:root { ... }` block right after that, and append our chaotic background CSS at the very bottom of the file.  

That’s all—clean, compatible, no warnings.  

You want me to read off the chaotic background CSS too so you don’t have to scroll for that either?

Ahh—okay, so what you’ve got isn’t just a stray `@themesInline`—it’s actually a **block** that holds your CSS variables and font definitions.  

That stuff is important, we’re not deleting it—we’re just moving it into normal CSS so the browser understands it.  

Here’s exactly how to do it:  

If you currently have something like:  
```css
@themesInline {
  color-background: #0f1113;
  color-foreground: #ffffff;
  font-sans: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  font-mono: 'Fira Code', monospace;
  /* etc… */
}
```

You change it to:  
```css
:root {
  --color-background: #0f1113;
  --color-foreground: #ffffff;
  --font-sans: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  --font-mono: 'Fira Code', monospace;
  /* etc… */
}
```

### Why:
- In CSS, variables must start with `--` and live inside a selector (like `:root`).
- This way, you keep **all** your theme values, but in a way Tailwind + browsers recognize.
- Your Tailwind config can still pull from these variables if you want.

So the final **top** of `globals.css` would be:  
```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;

:root {
  --color-background: #0f1113;
  --color-foreground: #ffffff;
  --font-sans: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  --font-mono: 'Fira Code', monospace;
  /* all the rest of your theme vars */
}
```

Then after all that, at the very bottom, paste the chaotic background styles we made.  

If you want, I can rewrite **your exact block** with all the variables you’ve got right now, so it’s copy-paste ready without you having to manually add the `--` everywhere. Want me to do that?

Yep—that’s all you need to do, King.  

Kill the `@theme inline { … }` line, keep everything inside it, but wrap it like this instead:  
```css
:root {
  --color-background: #0f1113;
  --color-foreground: #ffffff;
  --font-sans: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  --font-mono: 'Fira Code', monospace;
  /* rest of your variables exactly as they were */
}
```

No other changes to the rest of the file, and leave your chaotic background code at the bottom just as you already put it.  

That’ll fix the “unknown rule” complaint and keep your theme variables intact.

